  "slug": "fasolada",
  "title": "Fasolada",
  "subtitle": "Greek white bean soup with tomato and olive oil",
  "excerpt": "A thick, sustaining soup of white beans, tomato, celery, and carrot, finished with a generous pour of olive oil. Known as the national dish of Greece, this is winter cooking at its simplest.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Fasolada has been the staple Greek winter soup for centuries, documented in Claudia Roden's The Food of Italy (1989) and Diane Kochilas's The Glorious Foods of Greece (2001). The dish appears in virtually identical form across the Balkans and Aegean. Fasolada was the food of fasting days in the Greek Orthodox calendar (no meat, no dairy), which is why it was cooked so frequently and associated with Greek identity. During the Ottoman period it fed armies and monasteries.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fasolada is often called the national dish of Greece. It is cheap, filling, made from things that keep well, and tastes better the longer it sits. The soup is simple: white beans, tomato, carrot, celery, onion, and a generous pour of olive oil. The simplicity is the point.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Use dried beans if you have them and the time (soak overnight, cook for 60 to 90 minutes in fresh water before proceeding). Tinned haricot or cannellini beans give a good result and cut the time to under 30 minutes. Either way, finish the soup with olive oil added off the heat. It doesn't cook in, it sits on top in a pool that you stir through at the table.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
